<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-09-19T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-09-19T07:00:00-05:00" n="344" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d344">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">868.48/115: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner at Constantinople</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bristol</hi></persName>)
                                <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-09-19T15:00:00+03:00"><hi rend="italic">September 19,
                                        1922—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 9:44
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>193. Referring my telegram number 192, September 19, 4 p.m. Following
                            repeated from Smyrna for the Department’s information.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“Eighteenth. Italian Admiral conferred with Kemal who said would not
                                take responsibility allow Greek ships Smyrna. He will ask Government
                                and inform Admiral. Military Governor and staff left with regiment;
                                new Governor Colonel Madja Bey. American citizen Mr. Tara killed
                                about 4 days ago at his house; will bury to-day. U.S.S. <hi rend="italic">Edsall</hi>”.</p>
                        </quote>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bristol</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>